Dear Eileen,<br><br>
I, like the others here, have great respect for the decision your Dad made.  I too made a like decision when I joined the USAF.  After serving over three years, starting in 1967, I was due to be discharged without going to Vietnam.  I spent several weeks on a decision of whether or not to go, as I would have to volunteer.  I finally did, and extended my enlistment to do so.  But soon after getting there, and assessing what was happening, I decided to try leaving early.  I applied for, and finally received, an early out off my extention to go back to school.  <br><br>
I found out about some deaths in my unit after I left just last year.  There is a lot to reflect upon from Vietnam duty, and this war has affected each and every person in the United States, and also in Southeast Asia.  We will not know the ramifications of the war for many years to come, as these events are still playing themselves out. <br><br>
Thank you for your inquiry.  If you wish to see how another girl who lost her dad has decided to put his memory on the web, look at:<br><br>
http://members.aol.com/berly100/OurDad.html<br><br>
Best wishes,
